</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1834,2003]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1436,151,320]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knollner" authorityYear="1935" box="[199,315,1834,1859]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,315,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Aktedrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species producing spermatophores show a different degree of development of glandular tissues in the ectal part of the male duct. The conspicuous, glandular, pendant organ in the ectal section of the atrium may function both in the formation of spermatophores and as copulatory organ related to the attachment of spermatophores during mating (
<figureCitation box="[519,641,1942,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[295,1299,919,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[283,1303,911,1628]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Aktedrilus species forming spermatophores (from Swedish Museum of Natural History collection). A. A. mediterraneus (Erséus, 1980), spermatophore in segment XI. B–C. A. arcticus (Erséus, 1978), histological sections of the male duct. D. A. labeosus (Baker &amp; Erséus, 1982), copulatory bursa and glandular organ. E,F. A. mediterraneus, histological sections of the male duct. Abbreviations: a atrium, cb copulatory bursa, go glandular organ, gr glandular ring, ms male sac, o ovary, sf sperm funnel, sph spermatophore, vd vas deferens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1451102/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Fig. 4B–F</figureCitation>
). Although referred to as a 'penis' in some species, this organ is not associated with conspicuous musculature. The copulatory organ is enclosed in a bulbous male sac (usually described as a &quot;penial sac&quot;), which is the ental section of the copulatory bursa. In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Baker &amp; Erseus" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[1055,1184,151,176]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="labeosus">
<emphasis box="[1055,1072,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1086,1184,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">labeosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Erseus" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[1237,1429,151,176]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mediterraneus">
<emphasis box="[1237,1429,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">A. mediterraneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the copulatory organ is encircled by a large glandular ring or a pair of lips (
<figureCitation box="[994,1115,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[295,1299,919,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[283,1303,911,1628]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Aktedrilus species forming spermatophores (from Swedish Museum of Natural History collection). A. A. mediterraneus (Erséus, 1980), spermatophore in segment XI. B–C. A. arcticus (Erséus, 1978), histological sections of the male duct. D. A. labeosus (Baker &amp; Erséus, 1982), copulatory bursa and glandular organ. E,F. A. mediterraneus, histological sections of the male duct. Abbreviations: a atrium, cb copulatory bursa, go glandular organ, gr glandular ring, ms male sac, o ovary, sf sperm funnel, sph spermatophore, vd vas deferens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1451102/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 4D–F</figureCitation>
). In other species, such as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Erseus" baseAuthorityYear="1978" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="arcticus">A. arcticus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
a very thick epithelium of the so-called 'penis' (
<figureCitation box="[826,942,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[295,1299,919,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[283,1303,911,1628]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Aktedrilus species forming spermatophores (from Swedish Museum of Natural History collection). A. A. mediterraneus (Erséus, 1980), spermatophore in segment XI. B–C. A. arcticus (Erséus, 1978), histological sections of the male duct. D. A. labeosus (Baker &amp; Erséus, 1982), copulatory bursa and glandular organ. E,F. A. mediterraneus, histological sections of the male duct. Abbreviations: a atrium, cb copulatory bursa, go glandular organ, gr glandular ring, ms male sac, o ovary, sf sperm funnel, sph spermatophore, vd vas deferens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1451102/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 4B,C</figureCitation>
) also suggests a glandular function. Most 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knollner" authorityYear="1935" box="[151,267,260,285]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,267,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Aktedrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have some form of male sac, but in the species producing spermatophores, the ectal end of atrium is joined to a more or less enlarged and folded copulatory bursa (long in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Baker &amp; Erseus" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[1044,1173,295,320]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" genus="Aktedrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="labeosus">
<emphasis box="[1044,1173,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">A. labeosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1187,1277,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1650,1672]" captionTargetBox="[295,1299,919,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[283,1303,911,1628]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 4. Aktedrilus species forming spermatophores (from Swedish Museum of Natural History collection). A. A. mediterraneus (Erséus, 1980), spermatophore in segment XI. B–C. A. arcticus (Erséus, 1978), histological sections of the male duct. D. A. labeosus (Baker &amp; Erséus, 1982), copulatory bursa and glandular organ. E,F. A. mediterraneus, histological sections of the male duct. Abbreviations: a atrium, cb copulatory bursa, go glandular organ, gr glandular ring, ms male sac, o ovary, sf sperm funnel, sph spermatophore, vd vas deferens." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1451102/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
